50|$|In the mid-1990’s, Brooks {{read about}} {{the case of a}} 21-year-old Chicago women, Marilyn Mulero, who had been sentenced to death without a trial, based on a <b>plea</b> <b>bargain.</b> The {{situation}} made no sense to Brooks: virtually always, a defendant <b>plea</b> <b>bargains</b> for a lesser sentence, yet Mulero had received the harshest possible sentence.|$|R
